<font color="#FF0000">VETERANS CAN BE HEROES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar 18  2:05:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
JJ,<br><br>
Wow.  That is a really intense and vivid description of what it is like to fight to the death.  Reading your description, I can sense the horror.  I can almost feel the panic.  And that's just sitting here in my cozy little apartment, never having experienced anything even remotely like battle.  I can really see how that would tear you up inside.  I can see how that could wake you up in a cold sweat 30 years later.  The fear makes perfect sense, of course.  You saw right before you and by your own hand you had demonstrated what very likely could be your own fate at any moment.<br><br>
How do you heal from that experience?  A few ideas come to mind.  Asking for forgiveness from those you killed.  And forgiving yourself.  And if you can forgive yourself, then maybe you can also know that you are forgiven by those you killed, for they were in the very same predicament you found yourself in, and of course they would have done the same to you if they could have, right?  So if you can forgive yourself for what you had to do (you had no choice), and you can forgive the enemies who tried their best to kill you (they had no choice, either, given the situation they found themselves in), and if you can forgive those who killed your buddies, and if you can imagine that they had succeeded in killing you and that even then you would have forgiven them, then by logic you should consider yourself forgiven by those you killed.  Please understand that America has forgiven you.  I don't think America really ever blamed you.  I think they worked to demoralize you as one strategy to end the war, and the nation was bitterly divided and it was a very confusing, painful time.  But now that the dust has settled, nobody holds the combat veterans to blame, except maybe a few who have never let go of that era and moved on, like somebody at this site who shall remain nameless. ;-)  Forgiving the enemy, so that you can be forgiven and forgive yourself, is an important step I think.  Maybe that's what Tom is doing when he writes &quot;I feel much compassion for the Vietnamese. The men I fought alongside and the men I fought against were courageous.&quot; <br><br>
Another idea that comes to mind would be visiting Vietnam.  Or somehow having a relationship and/or dialogue with some Vietnamese who fought in the war on the other side.  I think it would be really cool and valuable if any former VC or North Vietnamese who engaged in battle could access this site and have converstations with you.  Hopefully positive conversations, of course, but any sort of communication would be good.<br><br>
The other way to heal is to help others who suffer in the same way that you are, and of course that is exactly what you guys are doing for each other at this site.  Maybe thats why I'm here too.<br><br>
I think I'm starting to understand one of the reasons I feel I can relate to you guys, even though I've never been in battle.  I experienced some very traumatic events many times in my childhood.  Athough I don't think I suffer from PTSD, I have suffered other anxiety disorders.  I know what it's like to feel like your soul has been torn to shreds and is bleeding, even though on the outside you look perfectly normal.  I know what its like to have a perfectly normal event cause you to break out in heart palpitations and a cold sweat.  I really hate admitting this in public, and I hope nobody I know reads this, because it's not something I like to make public.  But I want you guys to know that to an extent I can relate.  I don't think what I experienced is anywhere near as bad as what you guys did, but I have felt enough psycological trauma and its after effects so that I can at least imagine where you are coming from.<br><br>
It has taken me over 10 years, but I am starting to feel somewhat normal finally.  I know that time heals all wounds,  especially if you are willing to face them and deal with them as you guys are here.  I think it has made me a stronger person, a deeper person, and a more compassionate person.  I think the ultimate horrors you guys experienced can end up making *you* guys the ultimate American heroes.<br><br>
I once read that the final step in healing is helping others to heal.  That implies that those who have sufferred the same traumas are in the best position to relate to others who are hurting, hence this site.  But there is one other conclusion to that thought, and that is since combat veterans are the only ones who have experienced the true hell of mortal combat, maybe you guys are the best ones to heal the world of the sickness of War.  I believe there is an organization called Vietnam Veterans for Peace.  Maybe some of you guys could consider joining that.  Another great organization is Peace Action.  It costs $35 a year and they are doing great work in advancing the peace movement.  If you guys can help prevent future kids from going to battle and suffering what you have suffered, then all of your suffering will not have been in vain, but will have profound meaning.<br><br>
Tom writes &quot;Who do we look up to in this day and age? The politicians whom we ridicule by force of habit? Are sports heroes really heroes in the true sense of the word?&quot;.  I know who my heroes are.  I know my heroes are war veterans who have become peace activists.  I never felt such respect and admiration as I did when I saw old WWII Veterans as well as Vietnam Veterans marching for peace during the Gulf War.<br><br>
Maybe Vietnam Veterans are the heroes that America needs.  Sometimes it seems like America's spirit somehow died in the 60s.  It has been pretty bleak since then.  We are a divided country and a lost people in many ways. <br><br>
You guys are the ones who are witness to the horror and senselessness of war.  Please don't let that be in vain.  Help us see how good young boys were forced to become murderers.  Help us understand how and why this happenned.  Yes, it's hard to listen to a spoiled, rich, white college student screaming that war is wrong.  In several Vietnam War movies I have seen, they show Vets back from the War saying &quot;What the hell do those god damned protestors know?  Were they there?&quot;  That's true.  You guys are the ones who *really* know, and people will listen to what you say about war.  You guys were the true patriots, so who can attack your patriotism if you denounce any particular military policy or foreign policy of the U.S. government?  Have you heard about Col. Hackworth?  He is billed as the most decorated American soldier living today, and he has also been one of the biggest critics of the Vietnam War, of which  of course he is a veteran (see www.hackworth.com).<br><br>
Would you send another generation of young men to the same fate that has been yours?  If not, then please join me in preventing the military-industrial complex from ever again intervening violently in the political affairs of other nations.  Join me in fighting to end weapons sales to other countries, either for profit or for any other reason.<br><br>
War is a horrible thing and even in victory it should be treated like a funeral procession, not a party.  It should only be entered into as a last resort, and strictly in defending our own borders.  Even though we may sympathize with the plight of another country, we only make matters worse by stepping into the fray and/or being the world's weapons merchant.<br><br>
You guys have more moral authority in the area of war than any other living Americans.  Therefore you have more power than any other Americans (other than officials holding positions of power in government) to influence that policy.  I know you would not wish for any future generation of young men to travel halfway around the planet to kill (and die inside, if not in fact), only to come back to a scornful or indifferent nation.  Join me in demanding that the only future war we will engage in is one in defense of our own homeland, and that all weapons manufactured in the U.S. will be strictly for the use of the U.S. Armed Forces, not for sale on the international market, or for aiding one side or the other in a war between other countries.<br><br>
I know you can come up with situations where war might be justified besides defending our own borders.  But I can come up with many more real examples from the very recent past where the justification of US military intervention is questionable at best.<br>

<p><code>-- css@webcom.com  (Chris Schefler) </code><p>


